##4. Understanding data in Pure Data
In this workshop, we mainly work with a few essential types of data:

float: a simple number, such as a sensor value, a frequency, a threshold, or a volume level
bang: a trigger that launches an action
symbol: text or a command
list: several elements grouped together
audio signal: a continuous sound stream

This distinction matters because Pure Data objects do not all accept the same kind of input. Some objects expect numbers, some expect commands, and others work only with audio signals.

For example:
comport receives serial data from the Arduino
clip limits a value to a useful range
t f f f duplicates one incoming number and sends it to several destinations at the same time
metro generates a regular timing pulse
random introduces variation
mtof converts a MIDI note number into an audible frequency
osc~ creates a waveform
vline~ shapes sound over time
lop~ softens the sound by cutting high frequencies
delwrite~ / delread~ create delay and resonance
dac~ sends sound to the speakers
Understanding these objects helps participants see that a patch is not magic: it is a chain of simple operations, each with a clear role.


##5.Turning data into sound
Once the values arrive in Pure Data, they can be turned into sound through a sequence of operations. A simple version of this process can be described like this:

Sensor → Arduino → comport → data processing → sound synthesis → audio output

The first stage is data processing. Incoming values are often unstable, noisy, or too broad in range to be used directly. They may need to be:
limited,
smoothed,
compared to a threshold,
or distributed across different branches of the patch.

A single sensor value can then control several parameters at once. For instance, the same incoming number can influence:
the pitch of a sound,
the opening of a filter,
the tempo of a pulse,
the density of sonic events,
or the amount of echo and resonance.

This is one of the most interesting ideas in Pure Data: a value is not tied to one single meaning. It can be sent to multiple parts of the patch and translated into several simultaneous sonic effects.
In the next stage, the patch generates sound. An oscillator such as osc~ can produce a simple waveform, while vline~ shapes its evolution in time. A filter such as lop~ can soften the sound, and a delay can add resonance or spatial depth.
The result is not a direct “sound of the plant,” but a designed sonic response based on the changing values coming from the living signal.

##6. Experimenting

Once the basic patch is working, the workshop opens into experimentation.
At this point, participants can begin to modify the behavior of the sonic system. The same signal can generate very different results depending on how it is mapped inside the patch.
For example, participants can:

make the sound softer or brighter
add more or less delay
change the shape of the envelope
slow down or accelerate the triggering of events
create a denser or more minimal texture
move from short impulses to long resonant tones
build a sound world that feels rhythmic, liquid, airy, organic, or unstable

This is where the workshop becomes exploratory rather than purely technical. The goal is not only to make the system work, but to ask how different sonic translations affect our perception of the signal.
Two people can start from the same incoming data and produce very different listening experiences. One may build something close to drops or pulses; another may create a slow drone or a granular texture. Both are valid interpretations.
This stage is essential because it shows that sonification is not neutral. It is always shaped by aesthetic choices.


##7. Listening differently

This workshop proposes a different mode of listening.
The aim is not to prove that a plant literally “speaks,” nor to claim that sound reveals a hidden truth in a direct or objective way. Instead, the workshop creates a situation in which weak and usually imperceptible variations become audible through a technical and artistic process.
What we hear is not the plant alone, and not the machine alone. It is a relationship between:
a living signal,
an electronic circuit,
a microcontroller,
a software patch,
and a human act of interpretation.

In that sense, sound becomes an interface. It allows participants to pay attention differently, to imagine differently, and to reflect on how technology can mediate the living world.
Listening here is therefore not only a technical act. It is also an aesthetic and conceptual one.




